{\listtext	\'95	}1 cup {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/apple/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 apple}} juice\
{\listtext	\'95	}Salt and freshly ground black pepper\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 tablespoon butter\
{\listtext	\'95	}Chile Oil\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 cup chile powder, such as ancho, chimayo, or pasilla\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 tablespooon ground {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cumin/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 cumin}}\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 teaspoon salt\
{\listtext	\'95	}3 cups canola oil\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural
\cf0 For the Five-Spice Apples: Heat a medium skillet over medium heat. Add the oil and swirl to coat the bottom of the pan. When the oil shimmers, add the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/onion/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 onion}} and saute, stirring, until brown, about 8 to 10 minutes.\
Add the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/five-spice-powder/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 five-spice powder}}, brown sugar, apples, and juice. Stir, season with salt and pepper to taste, and cook until the liquid is reduced by half, about 12 minutes. The apples should retain their shape and some liquid should remain in the pan; do not overcook. Stir in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/butter/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 butter}} and correct the seasonings. Serve warm.\
For the Chile Oil: In a medium skillet, combine the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/chile/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 chile}} powder, cumin, and salt, and heat over medium heat just until the mixture begins to smoke. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/whisk/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Whisk}} in the oil and remove from the stove.\
Allow the chile oil to cool, transfer it to a glass jar, and let stand overnight. Cover and use or store. The oil will separate from the solids; use the red oil only.}